definition:
Any graph that contains no cycles is an *acyclic graph*. A directed
acyclic graph is often called a DAG for short.

For example, the following graph and digraph are acyclic.

$$\begin{array}{cc}
\xymatrix{&A\ar@{-}[dl]\ar@{-}[dr]\\B&&C}
\quad
&
\quad
\xymatrix{&A\ar[dr]\\B\ar[ur]\ar[rr]&&C}
\end{array}$$

In contrast, the following graph and digraph are *not* acyclic, because
each contains a cycle.

$$\begin{array}{cc}
\xymatrix{&A\ar@{-}[dl]\ar@{-}[dr]\\B\ar@{-}[rr]&&C}
\quad
&
\quad
\xymatrix{&A\ar[dr]\\B\ar[ur]&&C\ar[ll]}
\end{array}$$
